"Lal R.","Soil carbon sequestration impacts on global climate change and food security",2004,"Science","304","5677",,"1623","1627",,,10.1126/science.1097396,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-2942636040&partnerID=40&md5=e88f12e75678695ccab9b091c7b094e9","Carbon Mgmt. and Sequestration Ctr., Ohio State University, Columbus, OH 43210, United States","Lal, R., Carbon Mgmt. and Sequestration Ctr., Ohio State University, Columbus, OH 43210, United States","The carbon sink capacity of the world's agricultural and degraded soils is 50 to 66% of the historic carbon loss of 42 to 78 gigatons of carbon. The rate of soil organic carbon sequestration with adoption of recommended technologies depends on soil texture and structure, rainfall, temperature, farming system, and soil management. Strategies to increase the soil carbon pool include soil restoration and woodland regeneration, no-till farming, cover crops, nutrient management, manuring and sludge application, improved grazing, water conservation and harvesting, efficient irrigation, agroforestry practices, and growing energy crops on spare lands. An increase of 1 ton of soil carbon pool of degraded cropland soils may increase crop yield by 20 to 40 kilograms per hectare (kg/ha) for wheat, 10 to 20 kg/ha for maize, and 0.5 to 1 kg/ha for cowpeas. As well as enhancing food security, carbon sequestration has the potential to offset fossil-fuel emissions by 0.4 to 1.2 gigatons of carbon per year, or 5 to 15% of the global fossil-fuel emissions.",,"Agriculture; Biodegradation; Carbon; Climate change; Forestry; Rain; Soil structure; Soil texture; Soils; carbon; herbicide; agriculture; biomass; climate; cover crop; food; forestry; global climate; land use; no tillage; nutrient; priority journal; review; soil; soil quality; Agriculture; Atmosphere; Biomass; Carbon; Carbon Dioxide; Climate; Crops, Agricultural; Ecosystem; Food; Food Supply; Humans; Malnutrition; Poverty; Soil; Triticum aestivum; Zea mays",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Soil",,,,"Ruddiman, W., (2003) Clim. Change, 61, p. 261; (2000) Land Use, Land Use Change and Forestry, pp. 181-281. , Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge; Lal, R., (2001) Adv. Agron., 71, p. 145; Armstrong, R.D., (2003) Aust. J. Exp. Agric., 43, p. 141; Grace, P.R., (1995) Aust. J. Exp. Agric., 35, p. 857; Sa, J., (2001) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 65, p. 1486; Campbell, C.A., (2000) Can. J. Soil Sci., 80, p. 193; West, T.O., Post, W.M., (2002) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 66, p. 1930; Sauerbeck, D.R., (2001) Nutr. Cycling Agroecosyst., 60, p. 253; Silver, W.L., (2000) Restor. Ecol., 8, p. 394; Nordt, L.C., Wilding, L.P., Drees, L.R., (2001) Global Climate Change and Pedogenic Carbonates, pp. 43-63. , R. Lal, J. M. Kimble, H. Eswaran, B. A. Stewart, Eds. (CRC/Lewis, Boca Raton, FL); Levy, R., (1984) Chemistry of Irrigated Soils, pp. 182-229. , R. Levy, Ed. (Van Nostrand-Reinhold, New York); Lal, R., (2003) Crit. Rev. Plant Sci., 22, p. 151; West, T.O., Marland, G., (2002) Environ. Pollut., 116, p. 439; Follett, R.F., (2001) Soil Till. Res., 61, p. 77; Lal, R., Environ. Int., , in press; (2000) World Fertilizer Consumption, , IFDC, Muscle Shoals, AL; Smith, S.V., Renwick, W.H., Buddemeier, R.W., Crossland, C.J., (2001) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 15, p. 697; Lal, R., (2003) Environ. Int., 29, p. 437; Sanchez, P.A., (2002) Science, 295, p. 2019; Johnson, E., Heinen, R., (2004) Environ. Int., 30, p. 279; Lal, R., (2001) Assessment Methods for Soil Carbon, , CRC, Boca Raton, FL; Rosegrant, M.W., Cline, S.A., (2003) Science, 302, p. 1917; Lal, R., (2004) Science, 304, p. 393; Six, J., (2002) Agronomie, 22, p. 755; Smith, P., (2001) Nutr. Cycl. Agroecosyst., 60, p. 237; Pieri, C., (1986) Agron. Trop., 41, p. 1; Yamoah, C.F., (2002) Field Crops Res., 75, p. 53; Bauer, A., Black, A.L., (1994) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 58, p. 185; Johnston, A.E., (1986) Soil Use Manage., 2, p. 97; Diaz-Zorita, M., (2002) Soil Tillage Res., 65, p. 1; K